Interesting indeed. I really hope they do pull it off some day but I'm afraid I'm a bit of a pessimist. I don't think it's a realistic goal. Two hundred million dollars a year! Bloody hell. Thats nearly double Nasa's budget for nuclear spacecraft R&amp;D. What a waste of money. Much as I am in favour of any nuclear research including controlled fusion I think Bush has his priorities mixed up. 2037! More like 3037. Whats worse is that the anti-proliferation brigade uses fusion research as a target. Yales used to attack it because any research of that type can be applied to weaponry and breaches the aims of the CTBT. I don't give a fudge about it myself. I'm all for weapons research. But then I watch Bush telling other nations not to experiment with nuclear weapons programs and I see a bit of hypocrisy. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/03 3:34:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Controled fusion does exist. It is only a matter of time<br>
before it will become efficient enough to Replace<br>
old fashioned nuclear fission as an energy source for power reactors. I think it will happen long before 2037.<br>
At last report we have achieved the production of<br>
40% of the power input in fusion power generation.<br>
Also atomic rockets will be replaced by fusion rockets in the<br>
future, but the fusion rockets will still need  atomic reactors<br>
to serve as  batteries to provide the energy to ignite the fusion reaction in the fusion reactors/fusion engines.<br>
<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 44<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/10/03 11:13:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Actually we are a lot closer than most people think.  ITER, the proposed international fusion reactor would actually be able to output more energy than input.  It is <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>very possible with today's technology</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> to build a nuclear fusion plant.  However, the costs would be astounding and the electricity would hardly be competitive.  <br>
<br>
There is still a lot of &quot;basic&quot; physics we need to understand.  The progress in the last five years alone has been astounding, however.  I worked on a fusion experiment at the University of Wisconsin for the better part of a year and there is much steady progress in the field.  Perhaps I may be too optimistic, but everything seems to point to the technology working.<br>
<br>
200 million dollars is nothing.  The experiment I worked on (a small one) cost the government about 5 million to set up.  Both nuclear fission spacecrafts and fusion technologies need to be investigated heavily in my opinion.  We spend billions on maintaining a stockpile of nuclear weapons which could wipe out the world four times over.  Now, I'm not saying we should get rid of all of them, but I'm not sure about the wisdom of maintaining a stock of far more than we could ever need.  That Plutonium could go to much better uses that decaying in warheads. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=contraconstantius>contraconstantius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/11/03 10:09:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Unfortunately, fusion technology isn't enough for a fusion reactor. Even if the tech is ready in a year the greenies won't sit back and allow a fusion reactor to be built. Also the polititions have finall say about whether a comercial reactor is built. The best place to build a working fusion reactor might ge the moon, ceres, or somewhere else the ape in charge can't prohibit it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 131<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/11/03 10:22:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> I dont think theres any way that fusion could be stopped, once its feasible commerically.  <br>
<br>
The reason fission is unpopular is chernobyl and TMI.  if fusion is treated with caution, as it should be, then it can be touted as the power source of the future, of the stars, etc.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 688<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/11/03 3:37:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Never underestimate the tenacity of the radical anti-nuke movement.  I've already read numerous articles written by anti-nuke activists that believe <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> forms of nuclear power are wrong since they can release radiation into the environment and there's also that sub-group out there that think fusion generators should be banned globally because they believe they'll be used to make bomb-grade fuel.  The radical environmentalist, anti-human crowd hates everything nuclear.  Just watch when they try to build the first commercial fusion plant, I'll bet my life you'll see hordes of protestors out there. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 198<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/03 1:52:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> ANOTHER 35 years we're supposed to wait for this fusion baloney.  Maybe by then we'll be able to use something besides the DT fuel, because the estimates they give of radiation hazards are misleading, at best.<br>
<br>
Uranium isn't NEARLY as mobile as tritium is.  Yes, it has a short half-life, but that just means it is terribly active while it IS around.<br>
<br>
Modern PWR's until we can build Energy Amplifiers.  That's the way to go.<br>
<br>
Let's stop burning coal NOW. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/03 1:18:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> I agree.  However, fusion is better than fission if it can be made cheaply.  Btw, what do you mean by &quot;energy amplifiers&quot;? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 695<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/03 3:30:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Maybe if fusion would get serious funding we wouldn't have to wait another 50 years.  The world is hostile to the idea of fission and the best compromise is to develop an energy source that has similiar benefits but is easier to defend against the anti-nuke mobs.  Here's a good <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pnl.gov/energyscience/01-02/inside.htm">interview</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> with Rob Goldston about the state of fusion research.  It appears a weakness in previous fusion research has been a the lack of computing power for modelling fusion processes and seeing where breakdowns were occuring.  Working on a powersource that can generate megawatts out of a few cups of sea water sounds like something we should be working on in my opinion.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 203<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/15/03 11:35:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Fusion also has the benifit of widespread 'general public' support, something fission power lacks. I have even seen vehimitly anti-nuclear power people say fusion is the future and should be utilized. The public and the media by in large doesn't make the fusion-is-nuclear-too connection (yet), so one of the greatest hurdles against nuclear power is removed. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=contraconstantius>contraconstantius</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/15/03 4:13:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> Hmm. That's the first good news I've seen on this board. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 97<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/26/03 4:26:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.b5tech.net/art/b5/vorlonangry.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Bush Wants Fusion by 2037...</span><hr size=1> I wonder where fusion will be made practical, in big labs with equally big bureaucracies or in someone's garage. Some of the biggest breakthroughs happened that way.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 51<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/3/03 12:16:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=116.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   DIY Fusion!</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I wonder where fusion will be made practical, in big labs with equally big bureaucracies or in someone's garage. Some of the biggest breakthroughs happened that way.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
